Today, I was testing the PID for our robot, and at first it worked, moving to the exact position and stopping. Then, I tried to change our Constants.arm.Shoulder.gearRatio value and suddenly the arm didn’t move at all when I started the PID. I know that the PID is running because I had it print out something while the PID ran. Also, I outputted the encoder value of the motor as the PID ran and strangely, the encoder value was changing even though the motor wasn’t moving.
Here’s our github: 3984-2023/testing-Imported at NEW-Pid-test · DesteoyerRZSS/3984-2023 (github.com)

The shoulder gear ratio in your constants file is currently set to 0. In your arm subsystem you use that constant as a divisor in several places. Since the ratio is defined to be a double, the result of these divisions should be infinity (the positive infinity sentinel value in Java since your dividends are positive). You then pass this result to a spark max conversion factor function. I have no idea what those functions will do with infinity but I am sure it is not what you would want.

Lastly your gear ratio’s are 0 and since they aren’t causing an error by your own description you can safely assume that your conversion factor is effectively infinity (which SparkMAX’s may be smart enough to filter out and use the default).

Set your gear ratio to what it actually is, add in configuration of Brake or Coast mode, factory default at the beginning and burnFlash at the end.

I dont think you are using your feedforward right either but I could be wrong.
